      "writtenOn": "2026-05-18T20:58:05Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "To keep the logic in wait_no_sessions() simple, can we simply use the following to verify that a session still exist after a certain time period ?\n\n```\n# Check that sessions still exists before time_wait period\nself.virtual_sleep(8)\nsessions \u003d self.sessions()\nself.assertEqual(len(sessions), 1, \"Expected one session\")\n\n# Verify that session has expired after time_wait period has passed\nself.wait_no_sessions(timeout\u003d7)\n```",
      "revId": "a630eaaf346922c4f22f3bdced23faa2b2a7dc61",
      "serverId": "6d2eb258-4fe2-443e-8a38-ca81da23d4c2"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": false,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "0b6c9143_35220865",
        "filename": "test/test_sfdp_l4_lifecycle.py",
        "patchSetId": 16
      },
      "lineNbr": 433,
      "author": {
        "id": 1263
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-05-19T11:28:31Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "The point of should_fail\u003dTrue is to make test fail if the session is deleted too early, as that is the mechanism breaking CSIT tests (by allowing a responder packet to open a session in wrong direction).\nConversely, verifying the session lives long enough makes sure CSIT is not affected, without applying the more complicated and less general check of new reverse session appearing.",
